Serves 2-4Ingredients:2 x 500g lamb shanks3 Indian bay leaves (tej patha)5ml (1 tsp) turmeric powder4 cloves1 black cardamom pod4-5 black peppercorns2 x 2.5cm cinnamon sticks5ml (1 tsp) salt100g ghee (clarified butter)Asha's Spice Box: A glossary of exotic Indian ingredients1 large onion, sliced2 green cardamom pods15ml (1 tbsp) garlic-and-ginger paste2 green chillies, finely sliced1 large tomato, grated4-5 curry leaves30ml (2 tbsp) biryani masala spice mixture125ml ( cup) plain yoghurt1 carrot, sliced250ml (1 cup) peas125ml ( cup) chopped fresh mint and coriander200g (1 cup) uncooked basmati rice, soaked in cold water for 30 minutes, rinsed and drainedLamb & lentil bakeMethod:1) Place the lamb shanks in a deep pot with two of the Indian bay leaves, turmeric, cloves, black cardamom, peppercorns, cinnamon sticks and salt. Cover with cold water and bring to the boil. Reduce heat and simmer until meat is tender.2) Remove shanks from pot and set aside. Strain and reserve 250ml (1 cup) of the cooking liquid.3) Heat the ghee in another large pot and fry the onion until golden, then remove onion with a slotted spoon and set aside.4) Add the remaining bay leaf, green cardamom, ginger-and-garlic paste, chillies, tomato, curry leaves and masala mixture to the ghee in the pot and stir-fry for 2-3 minutes. Stir in the yoghurt and add the lamb shanks, carrots, peas, herbs, rice and strained reserved cooking liquid. Cover with a lid and cook on medium heat until all liquid is absorbed and rice is tender.5) Top with the fried onions and serve hot.